(8/8) It’s time to hold the cities that have brought homebuilding to a grinding halt accountable.

(6/8) My Build Now Act will incentivize new home construction by tying each city’s HUD grants to its rate of homebuilding.

https://t.co/n8eGr6qas2

(5/8) Los Angeles County, for example, has approved only 90 building permits since the wildfires in January. It received 1,200.

The federal government has an obligation to avoid wasting taxpayer dollars on cities that sacrifice the American Dream at the altar of overregulation.

(4/8) Congress, however, has a knack for taking complex problems and making them worse by forcing a one-size-fits-all solution on communities that we haven’t set foot in.

The housing problem must be solved at the local level, and this starts by removing nonsensical regulations.

(3/8) One reason young Americans are struggling to buy their first homes is that we aren’t building enough of them. New home construction is down nearly 5%.

The U.S. needs to increase its housing supply to put the American dream of homeownership back in reach.

(2/8) The market for first-time home buyers in America is dismal.

Since 2021, the annual income needed to qualify for a mortgage has increased by 60%, driving the median age of a first-time home buyer to 38—a record high.

🧵 (1/8) Buying your first home shouldn’t feel like a pipe dream.

It’s time to start incentivizing cities to make homeownership a reality for American families.

(5/8) The Spanish carveout isn't the only crack in NATO's commitment.

Under the new agreement, only 3.5% of each country's spending needs to contribute to core defense needs. The remaining 1.5% can apply to almost anything the country can claim is beneficial to its defense.

🧵 (1/8) NATO’s agreement to spend 5% of GDP on defense is a great accomplishment, but some of our friends have already begun to weasel their way out of this commitment.
